      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Return Run with Walk Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with 3 minutes of brisk walking to warm up the foot and ankle. Pay attention to any stiffness — this is normal and should ease within the first few minutes.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run easy at 5:58/km. If any foot discomfort arises, drop to a walk immediately — no need to push through. The goal is 14 minutes of comfortable, conversational effort. You should be able to speak in full sentences throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Finish with 3 minutes of easy walking. Gently roll the foot or do a light calf stretch if it feels tight.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 minutes of brisk walking before you begin running. This is especially important for plantar fasciitis — the fascia needs time to loosen up from its resting state.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3 minutes of walking, followed by a gentle standing calf stretch (30 seconds each side). Avoid aggressive stretching of the plantar fascia itself until cleared by your physio.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"James, you've done a really solid job building back up over the past two weeks — three runs, no significant pain, and you're hitting 20 minutes consistently. That's genuine progress, and it reflects smart, patient decision-making on your part. This Tuesday run keeps the same easy effort and duration you've been doing well with. The pace target is 5:58/km — the conservative end of your easy range — because your physio clearance is for easy running only, and protecting that foot is the priority right now. If you feel any foot pain at any point, walk it in. That's not a setback; that's the plan working as intended.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run — Consistency Builder\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 minutes of walking to wake up the foot. Notice how it feels compared to Tuesday — some day-to-day variation is completely normal.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy conversational running at 5:58/km. Two days after Tuesday's run, your foot should feel reasonably recovered. If stiffness lingers beyond the first 5 minutes (as you noticed on March 10), slow to a walk for 60–90 seconds, then resume.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk it out for 3 minutes. This is a good time to check in mentally — how did the foot feel today compared to Tuesday?\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes before running. If the foot feels notably stiffer than usual, extend the walk to 5 minutes before transitioning to running.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3-minute walk cooldown. Light calf and Achilles stretching is fine. If the foot feels tender after the run, a gentle ice massage (frozen water bottle rolled underfoot for 5–10 minutes) can help — check with your physio if you're unsure.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This Thursday run is your midweek consistency anchor. One of the most underrated parts of return-from-injury training is simply showing up at the same effort, same duration, two or three times a week — it builds both physical adaptation and confidence. You're not trying to do more today than Tuesday; you're reinforcing the same stimulus. Physiologically, this is where the tendon and fascial tissue do their quiet rebuilding work between sessions. The 48-hour gap from Tuesday gives adequate recovery without losing the training signal.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Weekend Long Run — Easy and Exploratory\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes. Saturday mornings can mean a colder, stiffer foot — give it extra time to loosen up. No rushing the warmup today.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"This is your 'long run' for the week — but at this stage of return, it's the same duration as your other runs. That's completely appropriate. Run easy, stay conversational, and treat this as an exploratory run: notice how the foot responds over the full 14 minutes. If you feel good at 14 minutes, resist the urge to keep going. Stopping when you feel good is a skill.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes. Take a moment to reflect on the week — three runs completed is a meaningful achievement at this stage.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3–5 minutes of walking before running. Saturday is your designated long run day per your preferences, and even though the duration matches your other runs right now, treating it with the same intentionality sets a good habit for when volume increases.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3-minute walk, then a full lower-leg routine: calf stretch, Achilles stretch, and whatever foot care your physio has recommended. This is the end of your training week — give the recovery some attention.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Your Saturday run closes out a three-run week — and at this point in your return, completing three easy runs without pain is the entire goal. Distance and pace will come back. Right now, the most important thing is demonstrating to your foot (and your nervous system) that running is safe again. You've already shown that over the past two weeks: March 15 was a run-walk, March 17 had no foot pain, and March 19 was a clean 20-minute run. That's a meaningful trajectory. This week, the target distance is listed as 4 km, but please treat duration (20 minutes) as the primary target — distance will vary slightly with pace, and that's fine. If at any point during the week you experience a return of foot pain that doesn't resolve within the first 5 minutes of a run, walk it in and reach out to your physio before the next session. That's not failure — that's exactly the right call.\",\"perceived_effort\":3}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
